    <node id="entity:360a2e1386408097d3d5">
      <data key="d0">entity:360a2e1386408097d3d5</data>
      <data key="d1">PERSON</data>
      <data key="d6">Marie Curie</data>
      <data key="d7">Marie Curie was a pioneering physicist and chemist, born in Warsaw, Poland, in 1867. She is renowned for her groundbreaking research on radioactivity, which led to the discovery of the elements polonium and radium. Her exceptional contributions to science earned her Nobel Prizes in both Physics and Chemistry. In addition to her research, she founded the Curie Institutes, which continue to be important centers for medical research. Marie Curie died from radiation-induced aplastic anemia, a condition resulting from her prolonged exposure to radioactive materials during her scientific work.</data>
      <data key="d9">0.02882</data>
      <data key="d10">1.0</data>
      <data key="d11" />
    </node>
    <node id="entity:8f3c37c7907288674eee">
      <data key="d0">entity:8f3c37c7907288674eee</data>
      <data key="d1">LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d6">Warsaw</data>
      <data key="d7">Warsaw is the capital city of Poland, notable as the birthplace of Marie Curie and the location of one of the Curie Institutes that she founded.</data>
      <data key="d9">0.009083</data>
      <data key="d10">1.0</data>
      <data key="d11" />
    </node>
    <node id="entity:17f73b43b68b92063205">
      <data key="d0">entity:17f73b43b68b92063205</data>
      <data key="d1">LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d6">Poland</data>
      <data key="d7">Marie Curie was born in Poland, her native country, and she later named the element polonium in honor of her homeland.</data>
      <data key="d9">0.017158</data>
      <data key="d10">1.0</data>
      <data key="d11" />
    </node>
    <node id="entity:efda500bef12d027bed2">
